quran[19]{c,v,t,f}:
67,27,"When they will see it near at hand, the faces of all those who had denied it will be distraught, {1} and then they will be told: “This is the doom which you used to ask for.”",footnotes:1:That is
67,28,"Say to them: “Did you ever consider: whether Allah destroys me and those that are with me, or shows mercy to us, who can protect the unbelievers from a grievous chastisement?” {1}",footnotes:1:When the Prophet (peace be upon him) started his mission in Makkah and the members of the different clans of Quraish began to embrace Islam
67,29,"Say to them: “He is Merciful, and it is in Him that we believe, and it is in Him that we put all our trust. {1} Soon will you know who is in manifest error.”",footnotes:1:That is
67,30,"Say to them: “Did you even consider: if all the water that you have (in the wells) were to sink down into the depths of the earth, who will produce for you clear, flowing water?” {1}",footnotes:1:That is
68,1,"Nun. By the pen and what the scribes write. {1}",footnotes:1:The great commentator Mujahid says that by pen here is meant the pen with which the Quran was being written down. From this it automatically follows that that which was being written implies the Quran itself.
68,2,"By your Lord's Grace, you are not afflicted with madness, {1}",footnotes:1:That is
68,3,"and surely yours shall be a never-ending reward, {1}",footnotes:1:That is
68,4,"and you are certainly on the most exalted standard of moral excellence. {1}",footnotes:1:Here
68,5,"So you will soon see, and they too will see,"
68,6,"which of you is afflicted with madness."
68,7,"Surely your Lord knows well those who have strayed from His Way just as He knows well those who are on the Right Way."
68,8,"Do not, then, yield to those who reject the Truth, decrying it as false;"
68,9,"they would wish you to be pliant so that they too may be pliant. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
68,10,"And do not yield to any contemptible swearer, {1}",footnotes:1:The word mahin is used for a contemptible
68,11,"the fault-finder who goes around slandering,"
68,12,"the hinderer of good, {1} the transgressor, the sinful; {2}",footnotes:1:Khayr in Arabic is used both for wealth and for good. If it is taken in the meaning of wealth
68,13,"the coarse-grained, and above all mean and ignoble; {1}",footnotes:1:The word zanim is used to describe a person of illegitimate birth
68,14,"(who so acts) simply because he has wealth and sons, {1}",footnotes:1:This sentence may be connected with the preceding theme as well as with the following sentence. In the first case
68,15,"and whenever Our verses are rehearsed to him, he says: “These are fairy- tales of times gone by.”"
